<h1>Scott Gilbertson</h1>

<h2><a href="/">/now</a>: <a href="https://luxagraf.net/now">luxagraf.net/now</a></h2>

<h2>Location:</h2>
<p>
Athens
GA
United States
</p>

<h2>Professional title:</h2>
<p>
Freelance writer for Wired, Ars Technica, The Register, etc.
</p>

<h2>What do you do?</h2>
<p>
I like to experience the world. And to tell stories.
</p>

<h2>Why?</h2>
<p>
John Muir said it better than me: "The world is big and I want to have a good look at it before it gets dark." I guess writing is my way of getting a good look at the world.
</p>

<h2>Recent thought or epiphany?</h2>
<p>
The last week or so I've been teaching myself to look from right-to-left when scanning a city/landscape. The idea is to force your brain to see rather than glossing over things quickly as your brain does when looking left-to-right (for someone of my culture anyway). I first heard about the idea from James Bridle's blog: <a href="http://booktwo.org/notebook/reading-right-to-left/">http://booktwo.org/notebook/reading-right-to-left/</a>
</p>

<h2>What should we read?</h2>
<p>
Gathering Moss: A Natural and Cultural History of Mosses by Robin Wall Kimmerer <a href="http://osupress.oregonstate.edu/book/gathering-moss">http://osupress.oregonstate.edu/book/gathering-moss</a>
</p>

